calendar file:

  1. listing_id: Unique identifier for each listing.
  2. date: Date for the listing's availability.
  3. available: Whether the listing is available on that date (true/false).
  4. price: Price of the listing per night.
  5. adjusted_price: Price adjusted based on discounts or surcharges.
  6. minimum_nights: Minimum number of nights a guest can book.
  7. maximum_nights: Maximum number of nights a guest can book.

listings file:

  1. id: Unique identifier for the listing.
  2. listing_url: URL to the listing on Airbnb.
  3. scrape_id: Identifier for the data scrape session.
  4. last_scraped: Date when the listing was last scraped.
  5. source: Source of the listing data (typically Airbnb).
  6. name: Name/title of the listing.
  7. description: Detailed description of the listing.
  8. neighborhood_overview: Overview of the neighborhood where the listing is located.
  9. picture_url: URL of the listing's main image.
  10. host_id: Unique identifier for the host.
  11. host_url: URL to the host's profile on Airbnb.
  12. host_name: Name of the host.
  13. host_since: Date when the host joined Airbnb.
  14. host_location: Location of the host.
  15. host_about: Personal description written by the host.
  16. host_response_time: How quickly the host typically responds.
  17. host_response_rate: Host's response rate as a percentage.
  18. host_acceptance_rate: Host's acceptance rate for booking requests.
  19. host_is_superhost: Indicates if the host is a "Superhost" (true/false).
  20. host_thumbnail_url: URL to the host's thumbnail image.
  21. host_picture_url: URL to the host's main image.
  22. host_neighbourhood: Neighbourhood where the host resides.
  23. host_listings_count: Number of listings the host manages.
  24. host_total_listings_count: Total number of listings associated with the host.
  25. host_verifications: Verification methods completed by the host.
  26. host_has_profile_pic: Indicates if the host has a profile picture (true/false).
  27. host_identity_verified: Indicates if the host's identity is verified (true/false).
  28. neighbourhood: Neighbourhood where the listing is located.
  29. neighbourhood_cleansed: Standardized neighborhood name.
  30. neighbourhood_group_cleansed: Larger grouping of neighborhoods (if available).
  31. latitude: Latitude coordinate of the listing.
  32. longitude: Longitude coordinate of the listing.
  33. property_type: Type of property (e.g., apartment, house).
  34. room_type: Type of room offered (e.g., entire place, private room).
  35. accommodates: Number of guests the listing can accommodate.
  36. bathrooms: Number of bathrooms.
  37. bathrooms_text: Descriptive text about the bathroom setup.
  38. bedrooms: Number of bedrooms.
  39. beds: Number of beds.
  40. amenities: List of amenities provided.
  41. price: Price of the listing per night.
  42. minimum_nights: Minimum number of nights required for booking.
  43. maximum_nights: Maximum number of nights allowed for booking.
  44. minimum_minimum_nights: Shortest minimum night requirement across booking windows.
  45. maximum_minimum_nights: Longest minimum night requirement across booking windows.
  46. minimum_maximum_nights: Shortest maximum night limit across booking windows.
  47. maximum_maximum_nights: Longest maximum night limit across booking windows.
  48. minimum_nights_avg_ntm: Average minimum nights required for future bookings.
  49. maximum_nights_avg_ntm: Average maximum nights allowed for future bookings.
  50. calendar_updated: How recently the calendar was updated.
  51. has_availability: Indicates if the listing has availability (true/false).
  52. availability_30: Number of available nights in the next 30 days.
  53. availability_60: Number of available nights in the next 60 days.
  54. availability_90: Number of available nights in the next 90 days.
  55. availability_365: Number of available nights in the next 365 days.
  56. calendar_last_scraped: Date when the calendar was last scraped.
  57. number_of_reviews: Total number of reviews for the listing.
  58. number_of_reviews_ltm: Number of reviews in the last 12 months.
  59. number_of_reviews_l30d: Number of reviews in the last 30 days.
  60. first_review: Date of the first review for the listing.
  61. last_review: Date of the most recent review.
  62. review_scores_rating: Overall rating score based on guest reviews.
  63. review_scores_accuracy: Accuracy rating based on guest reviews.
  64. review_scores_cleanliness: Cleanliness rating based on guest reviews.
  65. review_scores_checkin: Check-in process rating based on guest reviews.
  66. review_scores_communication: Communication rating based on guest reviews.
  67. review_scores_location: Location rating based on guest reviews.
  68. review_scores_value: Value-for-money rating based on guest reviews.
  69. license: License number for the listing (if applicable).
  70. instant_bookable: Indicates if the listing is available for instant booking (true/false).
  71. calculated_host_listings_count: Number of listings under the same host.
  72. calculated_host_listings_count_entire_homes: Number of entire home listings by the host.
  73. calculated_host_listings_count_private_rooms: Number of private room listings by the host.
  74. calculated_host_listings_count_shared_rooms: Number of shared room listings by the host.
  75. reviews_per_month: Average number of reviews the listing receives per month.

listings2 file:

  1. id: Unique identifier for the listing.
  2. name: Name/title of the listing.
  3. host_id: Unique identifier for the host.
  4. host_name: Name of the host.
  5. neighbourhood_group: Larger grouping of neighborhoods (if available).
  6. neighbourhood: Neighbourhood where the listing is located.
  7. latitude: Latitude coordinate of the listing.
  8. longitude: Longitude coordinate of the listing.
  9. room_type: Type of room offered (e.g., entire place, private room).

  11. minimum_nights: Minimum number of nights required for booking.
  12. number_of_reviews: Total number of reviews for the listing.
  13. last_review: Date of the most recent review.
  14. reviews_per_month: Average number of reviews the listing receives per month.
  15. calculated_host_listings_count: Number of listings under the same host.
  16. availability_365: Number of available nights in the next 365 days.
  17. number_of_reviews_ltm: Number of reviews in the last 12 months.
  18. license: License number for the listing (if applicable).

reviews file:

  1. listing_id: Unique identifier for the listing being reviewed.
  2. id: Unique identifier for the review.
  3. date: Date when the review was posted.
  4. reviewer_id: Unique identifier for the reviewer.
  5. reviewer_name: Name of the reviewer.
  6. comments: Comments left by the reviewer.

We have total of 21825 rows in our dataset and 18 columns. Out of which we are experiencing 6 columns carrying null values:

  • price (5289 - 24%)
  • reviews_per_month (5215 - 24%)

It is essential very essential for us to deal with null values. We can see that two columns having ~24% of data missing. it is too much data to delete or ignore. So, we should impute the data values for these two columns. Before choosing any imputation method let's check the distribution of both of these columns

In[10]:
# Visualizing the distribution of the above columns which to decide which imputation method we should use to fill in the missing values.

# Set up the plotting area for side-by-side plots
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize = (12, 4))

# Setting the Title of the plots
fig.suptitle('Distribution of Price and Reviews_Per_Month', fontsize = 15)

for i, col in enumerate(['price', 'reviews_per_month']):
    mean_val = listings2[col].mean()
    median_val = listings2[col].median()

    # Visualization - Histogram
    sns.histplot(listings2[col], bins = 30, color = 'skyblue', ax = axes[i], stat = 'count')

    # Visualization - axline for mean & median
    axes[i].axvline(mean_val, color = 'red', linestyle = '--', label = f'Mean: {mean_val:.2f}')
    axes[i].axvline(median_val, color = 'green', linestyle = '--', label = f'Median: {median_val:.2f}')

    # Titles and Labels
    axes[i].set_title(f'Distribution of {col}')
    axes[i].set_xlabel(col)
    axes[i].set_ylabel('Count')
    axes[i].legend()
    axes[i].grid()

    # Formatting the x-axis & y-axis
    def format_ticks(value):
        if value >= 1_000_000:
            return f'{value / 1_000_000:.0f}M'
        elif value >= 1_000:
            return f'{value / 1_000:.0f}K'
        else:
            return str(value)

    # Setting the axis' values
    axes[i].xaxis.set_major_formatter(ticker.FuncFormatter(lambda x, _: format_ticks(x)))
    axes[i].yaxis.set_major_formatter(ticker.FuncFormatter(lambda y, _: format_ticks(y)))

plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0, 1, 0.96])
plt.show()

As per the above visualization, we can see that in both of the columns' distribution the mean is getting affected by the skewness of the data. We can confirm with this that we should use Median Imputation Method.
Although, there are a lot of other imputation methods too but we will keep it simple for now.

In[11]:
# Median Imputation

# getting the medians of both the columns
median_price = listings2['price'].median()
median_reviews_per_month = listings2['reviews_per_month'].median()

# Imputing the missing values with their respective medians
listings2['price'].fillna(median_price, inplace = True)
listings2['reviews_per_month'].fillna(median_reviews_per_month, inplace = True)

listings2.isnull().sum()

We scaled the data as it is very imporant step for segmentation modeling. As in segmentation we use distance algorithms which will perform poorly if features are on different scales since they may give undue weight to features with larger ranges.
We will use K-means clustering algorithm. Let's apply Elbow Method in order to get the optimal clusters (K) for our model.

Finding Optimal Clusters

1. Elbow Method

In[21]:
# WCSS -  Within-Cluster Sum of Square

wcss = []
for k in range(1, 10):
    km = KMeans(n_clusters = k)
    km = km.fit(model_data)
    wcss.append(km.inertia_)

# Visualization - Line Plot
plt.plot(range(1, 10), wcss, 'bx-')

# Lableling
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('wcss')
plt.title('Elbow Method for Optimal K')

# Showing the Plot
plt.show()

Well, looking at the elbow method plot we can't really tell the optimal number of clusters. Although, we can still make an assumption & according to me, the optimal number of clusters should be 4. After 4, the line is descending at slow pace.
We got the optimal value But, to confirm if it is correct we can perform further analysis:

  • Silhouette Scores: This score measures how similar an object is to its own cluster compared to other clusters. Evaluating different k values using the Silhouette Score can provide additional confirmation of the optimal choice.
  • Visual Inspection of Clusters: Plotting and inspecting the clustered data can offer qualitative insights into the clustering results, helping to validate the choice of k.

2. Silhouette Scores

In[22]:
# Silhouette Scores

silh_scores = []
for n_clusters in range(2, 10):
    # KMeans for different n_clusters
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = n_clusters, random_state = 42)
    cluster_labels = kmeans.fit_predict(model_data)

    # Finding the Silhouette Scores
    silh_avg = silhouette_score(model_data, cluster_labels)
    silh_scores.append(silh_avg)
    print(f"For n_clusters = {n_clusters}, the silhouette score is: {silh_avg}")



# PLOTTING Silhouette Scores

# Setting plot/figure size
plt.figure(figsize = (10, 5))

# Visualization - Line Plot (Silhouette Scores)
plt.plot(range(2, 10), silh_scores, marker = 'o')

# Labeling
plt.title('Silhouette Scores for Different Values of k')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters (k)')
plt.ylabel('Silhouette Score')
plt.xticks(range(2, 10))

# For Gridlines
plt.grid()

# Showing the plot
plt.show()

As we can see according to the Silhouette Scores, the optimal cluster is coming up as 4 as the score of 4 clusters is the highest. It means, our previous observation aligns with our new analysis. Still, let's solidify our analyses more by visually plotting the clusters.

3. Visual Inspection of Clusters

In[23]:
# Setting up the plots
plt.figure(figsize = (20, 15))

for i, optimal_k in enumerate(range(2, 11)):
    # Using KMeans
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = optimal_k, random_state = 42)
    cluster_labels = kmeans.fit_predict(model_data)

    # Reducing the dimensionality for visualization (PCA - Principal Component Analysis)
    pca = PCA(n_components = 2)
    reduced_features = pca.fit_transform(model_data)

    # Creating a DataFrame for plotting
    plot_data = pd.DataFrame(reduced_features, columns = ['PC1', 'PC2'])
    plot_data['Cluster'] = cluster_labels

    # Creating a subplot for each cluster count
    plt.subplot(3, 3, i + 1)

    # Visualization - Scatter Plot
    plt.scatter(plot_data['PC1'], plot_data['PC2'], c = plot_data['Cluster'], cmap = 'viridis', alpha = 0.6)

    # Labeling
    plt.title(f'Clusters Visualization for {optimal_k} Clusters')
    plt.xlabel('PCA 1')
    plt.ylabel('PCA 2')
    plt.colorbar(label = 'Cluster Label')

    # Gridlines
    plt.grid()

# Adjust layout
plt.tight_layout()

# Showing all plots
plt.show()

In above clustering visualization, we visualized 9 plots ranging from n_cluster = 2 - 10. We can clearly see that the optimal value of k (n_clusters) is coming up as 4 her as well. We want to have as much cluster as we can get and the highest clean clusters we are getting is with optimal value of k as 4. So, by doing 3 different analyses we can confirm now that the otpimal value of k (n_clusters) = 4

Training

k-means Clustering Algorithm

In[24]:
clustered_model = model_data.copy()


if os.path.exists('./Models/Clustering/km.pkl'):
    print('Model Exists. Loading the model')

    # Loading the model
    km_model = joblib.load('./Models/Clustering/km.pkl')
else:
    print('Model not Found. Creating & Saving the model')

    # Clustering using the KMeans algorithm
    km_model = KMeans(n_clusters = 4, random_state = 42)
    km_model.fit(clustered_model)

    # Saving the model
    joblib.dump(kmeans, './Models/Clustering/km.pkl')


# Getting the predictions
km_predictions = km_model.predict(clustered_model)
clustered_model['PredictedCluster'] = km_predictions

Visualization

In[33]:
vis_data = clustered_data.copy()
In[34]:
# Defining the clusters along with their colors
clusters = ["Cluster 0", "Cluster 1", "Cluster 2", "Cluster 3"]
colors = ["lightcoral", "orange", "lightgreen", "lightblue"]

# Creating the custom legend entries
legend_patches = [Patch(color = colors[i], label = clusters[i]) for i in range(len(clusters))]

# Figure Size
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (2, 2))

# Shutting the axis
ax.axis("off")

# Adding Custom Color
fig.patch.set_facecolor('#dfedff')
ax.set_facecolor('#dfedff')

# Visualization - Legend
ax.legend(handles = legend_patches, loc = "center", fontsize = 10, title_fontsize = 12, 
          facecolor = '#dfedff', edgecolor = '#b5c7e7')

# Showing
plt.show()
In[35]:
# Grouping by 'PredictedCluster' and calculating the means
temp_data = vis_data.groupby("PredictedCluster").mean()

# Extracting insights for visualization
clusters = temp_data.index.astype(str)
prices_avg = temp_data["price"]
min_nights = temp_data["minimum_nights"]
reviews_avg = temp_data["number_of_reviews"]
availability_avg = temp_data["availability_365"]
host_listings_avg = temp_data["calculated_host_listings_count"]


# Creating subplots
fig, axs = plt.subplots(3, 2, figsize = (12, 12))

# Setting the background color for each subplot (axes)
for ax in axs.flat:
    ax.set_facecolor('#dfedff')

# Subplot title
fig.suptitle("Comparative Insights Across Clusters", fontsize = 16, y = 0.95)



# Visualization - BarGraph
axs[0, 0].bar(clusters, prices_avg, color = ['lightcoral', 'orange', 'lightgreen', 'lightblue'])

# Adding data values on bars
for i, v in enumerate(prices_avg):
    axs[0, 0].text(i, v + 5, f'{v:.2f}', ha = 'center', va = 'center', color = 'black', fontsize = 10)

# Labeling
axs[0, 0].set_title("Price Comparison")
axs[0, 0].set_ylabel("Average Price (CAD)")



# Visualization - Line Plot
axs[0, 1].plot(clusters, min_nights, color = 'gray', linestyle = '-', alpha = 0.5)

# Plotting each marker with different colors
for i, v in enumerate(min_nights):
    axs[0, 1].plot(clusters[i], v, marker = 'o', color = ['lightcoral', 'orange', 'lightgreen', 'lightblue'][i], markersize = 8)


# Adding data values on plot points
for i, v in enumerate(min_nights):
    axs[0, 1].text(i + 0.1, v - 0.1, f'{int(v)}', ha = 'right', va = 'bottom', color = 'black', fontsize = 10)

# Labeling
axs[0, 1].set_title("Minimum Nights Comparison")
axs[0, 1].set_ylabel("Average Minimum Nights")



# Visualization - Horizontal Bar Graph
axs[1, 0].barh(clusters, reviews_avg, color = ['lightcoral', 'orange', 'lightgreen', 'lightblue'])

# Adding data values on bars
for i, v in enumerate(reviews_avg):
    axs[1, 0].text(v, i, f'{v:.0f}', va = 'center', color = 'black', fontsize = 10)

# Labeling
axs[1, 0].set_title("Average Reviews Comparison")
axs[1, 0].set_xlabel("Number of Reviews")



# Visualization - Strip Plot for Availability
sns.stripplot(x = 'PredictedCluster', y = 'availability_365', data = vis_data, jitter = True, 
              palette = ['lightcoral', 'orange', 'lightgreen', 'lightblue'], ax = axs[1, 1])

# Adding data values on scatter points
for i, v in enumerate(availability_avg):
    axs[1, 1].text(i, v + 5, f'{v:.0f}', ha = 'center', va = 'bottom', color = 'black', fontsize = 10)

# Labeling
axs[1, 1].set_title("Availability Comparison")
axs[1, 1].set_ylabel("Days Available")
axs[1, 1].set_xlabel("Clusters")



# Visualization - Pie Chart with bold text, custom color, and legend
axs[2, 0].pie(host_listings_avg, autopct = '%1.1f%%', startangle = 90, 
              colors = ['lightcoral', 'orange', 'lightgreen', 'lightblue'], 
              textprops = {'color': 'black'})

# Labeling
axs[2, 0].set_title("Host Listings Comparison")


# Hiding empty subplot
axs[2, 1].axis("off")

# Layout adjustment
plt.tight_layout()

# Subplots adjustment
plt.subplots_adjust(top = 0.88)

# Showing
plt.show()
